<Author>oneword
<Content>Don't Do It! What a lousy welcome home to Australia after a few weeks enjoying the great service and amenities of Asian 4+ star hotels. In fact, I'm embarrassed that international visitors to Australia get some of their first impressions from this hotel.My wife and I arrived mid-evening after a pleasant Qantas flight from Hong Kong. We used the complimentary Mercure airport shuttle bus service which was easy to find and on-time. That was the one and only high point of our overnight stay.There is no porterage at the Mercure International Airport Hotel that we could find! Absolutely unacceptable, given that most international travellers have quite a bit of luggage. Our's was just unloaded out the front of the hotel and we lugged it inside where we queued to check-in. There was just one person on duty even though it was only 9:00pm. Again, not good enough. Eventually, a second person helped with check-in but by the time he turned up, most of the queue had been processed.The demeanour of both receptionists was, in a word, 'robotic'. No trace of warmth or genuine courtesy. We and our fellow travellers were just items to be processed as quickly as possible with as little interaction as possible. I witnessed a terrible episode involving an Asian couple who had travelled with us on the shuttle bus. After standing in line for 10 minutes and presenting their paperwork, they were told they were in the wrong Mercure Hotel. Their's was in the city. The couple had little English and the female receptionist did the absolute bar minimum to assist. She spoke to them like they were idiots and pointed outside the front door. Eventually, she ordered them a taxi but that was after several bewildered looks from the stranded couple. Their mistake was understandable and should have been handled with more diplomacy.Our non-smoking room had been smoked-in and the alleged refurbishment was at best, modest. We were too tired and Peed Off to complain and just wanted to hit the sack. The next morning, I told the receptionist about the smell in the room so that they could fumigate it. Her response? No sorry, no thanks for lettting us know. The best she could muster was well why didn't you complain when you checked-in last night! That's it, verbatim. Unbelieveable.We made the right decision the night before when we resolved not to stay a moment too long in the hotel, electing to eat breakfast at the airport rather than the downstairs restaurant. The last straw was the shuttle bus journey to the domestic airport in Sydney for our connection home. The driver was a lazy jerk who treated the bus load of guests like a major inconvenience and he drove like a maniac. Lots of hard acceleration and hard braking making the trip both uncomfortable and at times, nerve racking.Overall? Lousy service and attitude. The management team needs to be sent back to hospitality class, ASAP. 
